<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-135-110 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 793 598</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  June 4 1991 v5 n21 p28(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MagicBUS gives lift to PDS cards. (Processor Direct Slot) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ratcliffe, Mitch.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Sonic Systems Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Sonic Systems MagicBUS (Communications board) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionEthernetCommunications Boards/Cards.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Mitch RatcliffeandM;Cupertino, Calif.andP;  -- Sonic Systems Inc. last month released low-costEthernet adapters that install in the processor direct slots of the Mac IIsiand SE/30 but also allow users to mount other PDS cards in the single-slotmachines.andM;Priced at $299, Sonic's MagicBUS cards for the IIsi and SE/30 featurepass-through connectors that Sonic said support all standard 68030 PDS cards,including video, fax-modem and cache cards.andP;  The Sonic cards are available inthin coaxial or 10BASE T versions.andP;  All versions include a socket for anoptional floating-point processor, available from Sonic for $99.andM;In addition, both cards come with 16 Kbytes of static RAM, but managerswanting to improve throughput on intensive-use nodes can have the bufferupgraded to 64 Kbytes of SRAM at the time of purchase for $25.andM;EtherTalk Phase 1 drivers and System 7.0-compatible Phase 2 drivers, as wellas a diagnostic application called Inside Ethernet, are included free witheach MagicBUS.andP;  The boards are covered by a five-year warranty.andM;Sonic Systems Inc. is at 21211 Rainbow Drive, Cupertino, Calif.andP;  95014.andO;Phone (408) 725-1400; fax (408) 725-0759.andO;</TEXT></DOC>